<br>
Why?<br>
<br>
Because contrary to popular belief Everquest's main goal isn't the enjoyment of it's users. The main goal of Everquest is to provide revenue to SOE and it's stockholders. By far the greater portion of that revenue comes from monthly subsription fees as opposed to software sales. Enjoyment of users is secondary and probably only influences Verant's design process when a decision might lose existing long-term users. <br>
<br>
Everquest is a goal-orientated rather then process-orientated. I think It's safe to say that most Everquest users get the biggest thrill out of obtaining a reward from a difficult encounter or completing a lengthy quest rather then running around exploring or roleplaying. Items or skills which require large amounts of time to create of obtain satisfies the users which in turn continues SOE's monthly cash flow.<br>
<br>
If I were Verant I would consider upgrading existing epics slightly if I was worried about existing user turnover. For example I would throw Mages a bone and make the current epics a slight focus item. But I would definately make the Epic2 quests very time consuming AND very powerful to entice long-term players to keep sending those monthly fees in.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
